[src:tonic-grpc-rust/grpc] gRPC uses HTTP/2 for transport, Protocol Buffers as the interface description language, and provides features such as authentication, bidirectional streaming and flow control, blocking or nonblocking bindings, and cancellation and timeouts.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/grpc] It generates cross-platform client and server bindings for many languages.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/grpc] The most common usage scenarios include connecting services in a microservices style architecture, or connecting mobile device clients to backend services.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/grpc] gRPC's use of HTTP trailers makes it impossible to implement a gRPC client in a browser, instead requiring a proxy.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/grpc] From about 2001, Google created a general-purpose RPC infrastructure called Stubby to connect the large number of microservices running within and across its data centers.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/grpc] In March 2015, Google decided to build the next version of Stubby and make it open source.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/grpc] gRPC supports the usage of Transport Layer Security (TLS) and token-based authentication.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/grpc] Connection to Google services must use TLS.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/grpc] There are two types of credentials: channel credentials and call credentials.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/grpc] For token-based authorization, gRPC provides Server Interceptor and a Client Interceptor.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/grpc] gRPC uses Protocol Buffers to encode data.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/grpc] Protocol buffers provide a serialization format and an interface definition language.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/grpc] Some of the software tools used for testing gRPC implementations include Postman, ezy, Insomnia, and Step CI.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/grpc] Many organizations use gRPC, including Uber, Square, Netflix, IBM, CoreOS, Docker, CockroachDB, Arista Networks, Cisco, Juniper Networks, Spotify, Zalando, Dropbox, and Google as the original developer.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/grpc] The open source project u-bmc uses gRPC to replace Intelligent Platform Management Interface (IPMI).
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/grpc] On 8 January 2019, Dropbox announced that the next version of "Courier", their RPC framework at the core of their service-oriented architecture (SOA), would be migrated to be based on gRPC, primarily because it aligned well with their existing custom RPC frameworks.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] The standardization effort was supported by the Chrome, Opera, Firefox, Internet Explorer 11, Safari, Amazon Silk, and Edge browsers.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] Most major browsers had added HTTP/2 support by the end of 2015.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] About 97% of web browsers used have the capability (and 100% of "tracked desktop" web browsers).
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] As of July 2023, 36% (after topping out at just over 50%) of the top 10 million websites support HTTP/2.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] Its successor is HTTP/3, a major revision that builds on the concepts established by HTTP/2.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] The changes do not require any changes to how existing web applications work, but new applications can take advantage of new features for increased speed.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] HTTP/2 leaves all of HTTP/1.1's high-level semantics, such as methods, status codes, header fields, and URIs, the same.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] What is new is how the data is framed and transported between the client and the server.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] Websites that are efficient minimize the number of requests required to render an entire page by minifying (reducing the amount of code and packing smaller pieces of code into bundles, without reducing its ability to function) resources such as images and scripts.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] However, minification is not necessarily convenient nor efficient and may still require separate HTTP connections to get the page and the minified resources.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] HTTP/2 allows the server to "push" content, that is, to respond with data for more queries than the client requested.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] This allows the server to supply data it knows a web browser will need to render a web page, without waiting for the browser to examine the first response, and without the overhead of an additional request cycle.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] Additional performance improvements in the first draft of HTTP/2 (which was a copy of SPDY) come from multiplexing of requests and responses to avoid some of the head-of-line blocking problem in HTTP 1 (even when HTTP pipelining is used), header compression, and prioritization of requests.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] However, as HTTP/2 runs on top of a single TCP connection, there is still potential for head-of-line blocking to occur if TCP packets are lost or delayed in transmission.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] HTTP/2 no longer supports HTTP/1.1's chunked transfer encoding mechanism, as it provides its own, more efficient mechanisms for data streaming.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] SPDY (pronounced like "speedy") was a previous HTTP-replacement protocol developed by a research project spearheaded by Google.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] Primarily focused on reducing latency, SPDY uses the same TCP pipe but different protocols to accomplish this reduction.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] The basic changes made to HTTP/1.1 to create SPDY included "true request pipelining without FIFO restrictions, message framing mechanism to simplify client and server development, mandatory compression (including headers), priority scheduling, and even bi-directional communication".
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] The HTTP Working Group considered Google's SPDY protocol, Microsoft's HTTP Speed+Mobility proposal (SPDY based), and Network-Friendly HTTP Upgrade.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] In July 2012, Facebook provided feedback on each of the proposals and recommended HTTP/2 be based on SPDY.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] The initial draft of HTTP/2 was published in November 2012 and was based on a straight copy of SPDY.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] The biggest difference between HTTP/1.1 and SPDY was that each user action in SPDY is given a "stream ID", meaning there is a single TCP channel connecting the user to the server.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] SPDY split requests into either control or data, using a "simple to parse binary protocol with two types of frames".
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] SPDY showed evident improvement over HTTP, with a new page load speedup ranging from 11% to 47%.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] The development of HTTP/2 used SPDY as a jumping-off point.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] Among the many detailed differences between the protocols, the most notable is that HTTP/2 uses a fixed Huffman code-based header compression algorithm, instead of SPDY's dynamic stream-based compression.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] This helps to reduce the potential for compression oracle attacks on the protocol, such as the CRIME attack.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] On February 9, 2015, Google announced plans to remove support for SPDY in Chrome in favor of support for HTTP/2.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] This took effect starting with Chrome 51.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] HTTP/2 is defined for both HTTP URIs (without TLS encryption, a configuration which is abbreviated as **h2c**) and HTTPS URIs (over TLS using ALPN extension where TLS 1.2 or newer is required, a configuration which is abbreviated as **h2**).
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] Although the standard itself does not require usage of encryption, all major client implementations (Chrome, Edge, Firefox, Internet Explorer, Opera, Safari) have stated they will only support HTTP/2 over TLS, which makes encryption de facto mandatory.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] The FreeBSD and Varnish developer Poul-Henning Kamp asserts that the standard was prepared on an unrealistically short schedule, ruling out any basis for the new HTTP/2 other than the SPDY protocol and resulting in other missed opportunities for improvement.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] Kamp criticizes the protocol itself for being inconsistent and having needless, overwhelming complexity.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] He also states that the protocol violates the protocol layering principle, for example by duplicating flow control that belongs in the transport layer (TCP).
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] He also suggested that the new protocol should have removed HTTP Cookies, introducing a breaking change.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] Initially, some members of the Working Group tried to introduce an encryption requirement in the protocol.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] Critics stated that encryption has non-negligible computing costs and that many HTTP applications actually have no need for encryption and their providers have no desire to spend additional resources on it.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] Encryption proponents have stated that this encryption overhead is negligible in practice.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] Poul-Henning Kamp has criticized the IETF for hastily standardizing Google's SPDY prototype as HTTP/2 due to political considerations.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] In the end the Working Group did not reach consensus over the mandatory encryption, although most client implementations require it, which makes encryption a *de facto* requirement.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] The HTTP/2 protocol also faced criticism for not supporting opportunistic encryption, a measure against passive monitoring similar to the STARTTLS mechanism that has long been available in other Internet protocols like SMTP.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] Critics have stated that the HTTP/2 proposal goes in violation of IETF's own RFC 7258 "Pervasive Monitoring Is an Attack", which also has a status of Best Current Practice 188.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] RFC7258/BCP188 mandates that pervasive monitoring be considered as an attack, and protocols designed by IETF should take steps to protect against passive monitoring (for example, through the use of opportunistic encryption).
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] A number of specifications for opportunistic encryption of HTTP/2 have been provided, of which draft-nottingham-http2-encryption was adopted as an official work item of the working group, leading to the publication of RFC 8164 in May 2017.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/http-2] This head-of-line blocking in HTTP/2 is now widely regarded as a design flaw, and much of the effort behind QUIC and HTTP/3 has been devoted to reduce head-of-line blocking issues.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/interface-description-language] An **interface description language** or **interface definition language** (**IDL**) is a generic term for a language that lets a program or object written in one language communicate with another program written in an unknown language.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/interface-description-language] IDLs are usually used to describe data types and interfaces in a language-independent way, for example, between those written in C++ and those written in Java.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/interface-description-language] IDLs are commonly used in remote procedure call software.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/interface-description-language] In these cases the machines at either end of the *link* may be using different operating systems and computer languages.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/interface-description-language] IDLs offer a bridge between the two different systems.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/latest-tonic] A Rust implementation of gRPC, a high performance, open source, general RPC framework that puts mobile and HTTP/2 first.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/latest-tonic] `tonic` is a gRPC over HTTP/2 implementation focused on **high performance**, **interoperability**, and **flexibility**.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/latest-tonic] This library was created to have first class support of async/await and to act as a core building block for production systems written in Rust.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/latest-tonic] Examples can be found in the `tonic-examples` crate.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/latest-tonic] Follow the instructions in the `tonic-build` crate documentation.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/latest-tonic] The main goal of `tonic` is to provide a generic gRPC implementation over HTTP/2 framing.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/latest-tonic] This means at the lowest level this library provides the ability to use a generic HTTP/2 implementation with different types of gRPC encodings formats.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/latest-tonic] Generally, some form of codegen should be used instead of interacting directly with the items in `client` and `server`.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/latest-tonic] The `transport` module contains a fully featured HTTP/2.0 `Channel` (gRPC terminology) and `Server`.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/latest-tonic] These implementations are built on top of `tokio`, `hyper` and `tower`.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/latest-tonic] It also provides many of the features that the core gRPC libraries provide such as load balancing, tls, timeouts, and many more.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/latest-tonic] This implementation can also be used as a reference implementation to build even more feature rich clients and servers.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/latest-tonic] This module also provides the ability to enable TLS using `rustls`, via the `tls` feature flag.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/latest-tonic] Currently, both servers and clients can be configured to set the max message encoding and decoding size.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/latest-tonic] This will ensure that an incoming gRPC message will not exhaust the systems memory.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/latest-tonic] By default, the decoding message limit is `4MB` and the encoding limit is `usize::MAX`.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/latest-tonic] Contains data structures and utilities for handling gRPC custom metadata.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/latest-tonic] Utilities for using Tower services with Tonic.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/latest-tonic] Include generated proto server and client items.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/latest-tonic] Wrapper type to indicate that an error occurs during the connection process, so that the appropriate gRPC Status can be inferred.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/latest-tonic] A gRPC request and metadata from an RPC call.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/latest-tonic] A gRPC response and metadata from an RPC call.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/latest-tonic] A gRPC status describing the result of an RPC call.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/latest-tonic] Error returned if a request didn’t complete within the configured timeout.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/latest-tonic] Trait implemented by RPC streaming request types.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/protocol-buffers] Google developed Protocol Buffers for internal use and provided a code generator for multiple languages under an open-source license.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/protocol-buffers] The design goals for Protocol Buffers emphasized simplicity and performance.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/protocol-buffers] In particular, it was designed to be smaller and faster than XML.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/protocol-buffers] Protocol Buffers is widely used at Google for storing and interchanging all kinds of structured information.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/protocol-buffers] The method serves as a basis for a custom remote procedure call (RPC) system that is used for nearly all inter-machine communication at Google.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/protocol-buffers] Protocol Buffers is similar to the Apache Thrift, Amazon Ion, and Microsoft Bond protocols, offering a concrete RPC protocol stack to use for defined services called gRPC.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/protocol-buffers] Data structure schemas (called *messages*) and services are described in a proto definition file (`.proto`) and compiled with `protoc`.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/protocol-buffers] This compilation generates code that can be invoked by a sender or recipient of these data structures.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/protocol-buffers] For example, `example.pb.cc` and `example.pb.h` are generated from `example.proto`.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/protocol-buffers] They define C++ classes for each message and service in `example.proto`.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/protocol-buffers] Canonically, messages are serialized into a binary wire format which is compact, forward- and backward-compatible, but not self-describing (that is, there is no way to tell the names, meaning, or full datatypes of fields without an external specification).
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/protocol-buffers] There is no defined way to include or refer to such an external specification (schema) within a Protocol Buffers file.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/protocol-buffers] The officially supported implementation includes an ASCII serialization format, but this format—though self-describing—loses the forward- and backward-compatibility behavior, and is thus not a good choice for applications other than human editing and debugging.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/protocol-buffers] Though the primary purpose of Protocol Buffers is to facilitate network communication, its simplicity and speed make Protocol Buffers an alternative to data-centric C++ classes and structs, especially where interoperability with other languages or systems might be needed in the future.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/protocol-buffers] The format is best suited for small data chunks that don't exceed a few megabytes and can be loaded/sent into memory right away and therefore is not a streamable format.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/protocol-buffers] The library doesn't provide compression out of the box.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/protocol-buffers] The format also isn't well supported in non–object-oriented languages (e.g.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/protocol-buffers] A schema for a particular use of protocol buffers associates data types with field names, using integers to identify each field.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/protocol-buffers] The `Point` message defines two mandatory data items, `x` and `y`.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/protocol-buffers] The tag is defined after the equal sign.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/protocol-buffers] The `Line` and `Polyline` messages, which both use `Point`, demonstrate how composition works in Protocol Buffers.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/protocol-buffers] `Polyline` has a `repeated` field, and thus `Polyline` behaves like a set of points (of unspecified number).
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/protocol-buffers] This schema can subsequently be compiled for use by one or more programming languages.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/protocol-buffers] Google provides a compiler called `protoc` which can produce output for C++, Java or Python.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/protocol-buffers] Other schema compilers are available from other sources to create language-dependent output for over 20 other languages.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/protocol-buffers] Protobuf 2.0 provides a code generator for C++, Java, C#, and Python.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/protocol-buffers] Protobuf 3.0 provides a code generator for C++, Java (including JavaNano, a dialect intended for low-resource environments), Kotlin, Python, Go, Ruby, Objective-C, C#, PHP, Dart.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/protocol-buffers] It also supports JavaScript since 3.0.0-beta-2.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/protocol-buffers] Third-party implementations are also available for Ada, Ballerina, C, C++, Dart, Elixir, Erlang, Haskell, JavaScript, Julia, Nim, Perl, PHP, Prolog, R, Rust, Scala, and Swift.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/remote-procedure-call] That is, the programmer writes essentially the same code whether the subroutine is local to the executing program, or remote.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/remote-procedure-call] This is a form of server interaction (caller is client, executor is server), typically implemented via a request–response message passing system.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/remote-procedure-call] In the object-oriented programming paradigm, RPCs are represented by remote method invocation (RMI).
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/remote-procedure-call] The RPC model implies a level of location transparency, namely that calling procedures are largely the same whether they are local or remote, but usually, they are not identical, so local calls can be distinguished from remote calls.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/remote-procedure-call] Remote calls are usually orders of magnitude slower and less reliable than local calls, so distinguishing them is important.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/remote-procedure-call] Many different (often incompatible) technologies have been used to implement the concept.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/remote-procedure-call] Request–response protocols date to early distributed computing in the late 1960s, theoretical proposals of remote procedure calls as the model of network operations date to the 1970s, and practical implementations date to the early 1980s.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/remote-procedure-call] Bruce Jay Nelson is generally credited with coining the term "remote procedure call" in 1981.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/remote-procedure-call] Remote procedure calls used in modern operating systems trace their roots back to the RC 4000 multiprogramming system, which used a request-response communication protocol for process synchronization.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/remote-procedure-call] The idea of treating network operations as remote procedure calls goes back at least to the 1970s in early ARPANET documents.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/remote-procedure-call] In 1978, Per Brinch Hansen proposed Distributed Processes, a language for distributed computing based on "external requests" consisting of procedure calls between processes.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/remote-procedure-call] One of the earliest practical implementations was in 1982 by Brian Randell and colleagues for their Newcastle Connection between UNIX machines.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/remote-procedure-call] This was soon followed by "Lupine" by Andrew Birrell and Bruce Nelson in the Cedar environment at Xerox PARC.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/remote-procedure-call] Lupine automatically generated stubs, providing type-safe bindings, and used an efficient protocol for communication.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/remote-procedure-call] One of the first business uses of RPC was by Xerox under the name "Courier" in 1981.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/remote-procedure-call] The first popular implementation of RPC on Unix was Sun's RPC (now called ONC RPC), used as the basis for Network File System (NFS).
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/remote-procedure-call] In the 1990s, with the popularity of object-oriented programming, an alternative model of remote method invocation (RMI) was widely implemented, such as in Common Object Request Broker Architecture (CORBA, 1991) and Java remote method invocation.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/remote-procedure-call] RMIs, in turn, fell in popularity with the rise of the internet, particularly in the 2000s.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/remote-procedure-call] An RPC is initiated by the *client*, which sends a request message to a known remote *server* to execute a specified procedure with supplied parameters.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/remote-procedure-call] The remote server sends a response to the client, and the application continues its process.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/remote-procedure-call] While the server is processing the call, the client is blocked (it waits until the server has finished processing before resuming execution), unless the client sends an asynchronous request to the server, such as an XMLHttpRequest.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/remote-procedure-call] There are many variations and subtleties in various implementations, resulting in a variety of different (incompatible) RPC protocols.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/remote-procedure-call] An important difference between remote procedure calls and local calls is that remote calls can fail because of unpredictable network problems.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/remote-procedure-call] Also, callers generally must deal with such failures without knowing whether the remote procedure was actually invoked.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/remote-procedure-call] Idempotent procedures (those that have no additional effects if called more than once) are easily handled, but enough difficulties remain that code to call remote procedures is often confined to carefully written low-level subsystems.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/remote-procedure-call] The client stub packs the parameters into a message and makes a system call to send the message.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/remote-procedure-call] Packing the parameters is called marshalling.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/remote-procedure-call] The client's local operating system sends the message from the client machine to the server machine.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/remote-procedure-call] The local operating system on the server machine passes the incoming packets to the server stub.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/remote-procedure-call] The server stub unpacks the parameters from the message.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/remote-procedure-call] Unpacking the parameters is called unmarshalling.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/remote-procedure-call] Finally, the server stub calls the server procedure.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/remote-procedure-call] The reply traces the same steps in the reverse direction.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/remote-procedure-call] To let different clients access servers, a number of standardized RPC systems have been created.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/remote-procedure-call] Most of these use an interface description language (IDL) to let various platforms call the RPC.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/remote-procedure-call] The IDL files can then be used to generate code to interface between the client and servers.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports multiple programming paradigms.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] It was influenced by ideas from functional programming, including immutability, higher-order functions, algebraic data types, and pattern matching.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] It also supports object-oriented programming via structs, enums, traits, and methods.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust enforces memory safety (i.e., that all references point to valid memory) without a conventional garbage collector; instead, memory safety errors and data races are prevented by the "borrow checker", which tracks the object lifetime of references at compile time.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Software developer Graydon Hoare created Rust in 2006 while working at Mozilla, which officially sponsored the project in 2009.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The first stable release, Rust 1.0, was published in May 2015.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The project has been sponsored by the Rust Foundation since February 2021.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust has been adopted by many software projects, especially web services and system software.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] It has been studied academically and has a growing community of developers.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust began as a personal project by Mozilla employee Graydon Hoare in 2006.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] According to *MIT Technology Review*, he started the project due to his frustration with a broken elevator in his apartment building whose software had crashed, and named the language after the group of fungi of the same name that is "over-engineered for survival".
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] During the time period between 2006 and 2009, Rust was not publicized to others at Mozilla and was written in Hoare's free time; Hoare began speaking about the language around 2009 after a small group at Mozilla became interested in the project.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Hoare cited languages from the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s as influences — including CLU, BETA, Mesa, NIL, Erlang, Newsqueak, Napier, Hermes, Sather, Alef, and Limbo.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] During the early years, the Rust compiler was written in about 38,000 lines of OCaml.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Early Rust contained several features no longer present today, including explicit object-oriented programming via an `obj` keyword and a typestates system for variable state changes, such as going from uninitialized to initialized.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Mozilla officially sponsored the Rust project in 2009.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Brendan Eich and other executives, intrigued by the possibility of using Rust for a safe web browser engine, placed engineers on the project including Patrick Walton, Niko Matsakis, Felix Klock, and Manish Goregaokar.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] A conference room taken by the project developers was dubbed "the nerd cave," with a sign placed outside the door.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] During this time period, work had shifted from the initial OCaml compiler to a self-hosting compiler (*i.e.*, written in Rust) targeting LLVM.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The ownership system was in place by 2010.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust logo was developed in 2011 based on a bicycle chainring.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust 0.1 became the first public release on January 20, 2012 for Windows, Linux, and MacOS.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The early 2010s witnessed increasing involvement from full-time engineers at Mozilla and open source volunteers outside Mozilla.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The years from 2012 to 2015 were marked by substantial changes to the Rust type system.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory management through the ownership system was gradually consolidated and expanded.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] By 2013, the garbage collector was rarely used, and was removed in favor of the ownership system.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Other features were removed in order to simplify the language, including typestates, the `pure` keyword, various specialized pointer types, and syntax support for channels.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] According to Steve Klabnik, Rust was influenced during this period by developers coming from C++ (e.g., low-level performance of features), scripting languages (e.g., Cargo and package management), and functional programming (e.g., type systems development).
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Graydon Hoare stepped down from Rust in 2013.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] After Hoare's departure, it evolved organically under a federated governance structure, with a "core team" of initially six people, and around 30-40 developers total across various other teams.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] A Request for Comments (RFC) process for new language features was added in March 2014.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The core team would grow to nine people by 2016 with over 1600 RFCs.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Dobb's Journal* in January 2014, while Rust was "widely viewed as a remarkably elegant language", adoption slowed because it radically changed from version to version.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust development at this time focused on finalizing features for version 1.0 so that it could begin promising backward compatibility.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Six years after Mozilla's sponsorship, Rust 1.0 was published and became the first stable release on May 15, 2015.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] A year later, the Rust compiler had accumulated over 1,400 contributors, and there were over 5,000 third-party libraries published on the Rust package management website Crates.io.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The development of the Servo browser engine continued in parallel with Rust, jointly funded by Mozilla and Samsung.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The teams behind the two projects worked in close collaboration; new features in Rust were tested out by the Servo team, and new features in Servo were used to give feedback back to the Rust team.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The first version of Servo was released in 2016.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The Firefox web browser shipped with Rust code as of 2016 (version 45), but components of Servo did not appear in Firefox until September 2017 (version 57) as part of the Gecko and Quantum projects.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Improvements were made to the Rust toolchain ecosystem during the years following 1.0 including Rustfmt, integrated development environment integration, and a regular compiler testing and release cycle.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's community gained a code of conduct and an IRC chat for discussion.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The earliest known adoption outside of Mozilla was by individual projects at Samsung, Facebook (now Meta Platforms), Dropbox, and Tilde, Inc., the company behind ember.js.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Engineers cited performance, lack of a garbage collector, safety, and pleasantness of working in the language as reasons for the adoption.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Amazon developers cited a finding by Portuguese researchers that Rust code used less energy compared to similar code written in Java.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] In August 2020, Mozilla laid off 250 of its 1,000 employees worldwide, as part of a corporate restructuring caused by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The event raised concerns about the future of Rust.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] In the following week, the Rust Core Team acknowledged the severe impact of the layoffs and announced that plans for a Rust foundation were underway.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The first goal of the foundation would be to take ownership of all trademarks and domain names and to take financial responsibility for their costs.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] On February 8, 2021, the formation of the Rust Foundation was announced by five founding companies: Amazon Web Services, Google, Huawei, Microsoft, and Mozilla.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The foundation would provide financial support for Rust developers in the form of grants and server funding.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] In a blog post published on April 6, 2021, Google announced support for Rust within the Android Open Source Project as an alternative to C/C++.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] On November 22, 2021, the Moderation Team, which was responsible for enforcing the community code of conduct, announced their resignation "in protest of the Core Team placing themselves unaccountable to anyone but themselves".
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] In May 2022, members of the Rust leadership council posted a public response to the incident.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust Foundation posted a draft for a new trademark policy on April 6, 2023, which resulted in widespread negative reactions from Rust users and contributors.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The trademark policy included rules for how the Rust logo and name could be used.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's syntax is similar to that of C and C++, although many of its features were influenced by functional programming languages such as OCaml.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Hoare has described Rust as targeted at frustrated C++ developers.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Below is a "Hello, World!" program in Rust.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The `fn` keyword denotes a function, and the `println!` macro (see § Macros) prints the message to standard output.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Statements in Rust are separated by semicolons.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Variables in Rust are defined through the `let` keyword.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The example below assigns a value to the variable with name `foo` of type `i32` and outputs its value; the type annotation `: i32` can be omitted.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Variables are immutable by default, unless the `mut` keyword is added.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The following example uses `//`, which denotes the start of a comment.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Multiple `let` expressions can define multiple variables with the same name, known as variable shadowing.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing allows transforming variables without having to name the variables differently.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing is also possible for values of different types.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] A *block expression* is delimited by curly brackets.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] An `if` conditional expression executes code based on whether the given value is `true`.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] `else` can be used for when the value evaluates to `false`, and `else if` can be used for combining multiple expressions.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] `while` can be used to repeat a block of code while a condition is met.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] For loops in Rust loop over elements of a collection.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] `for` expressions work over any iterator type.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] In the above code, `4..=10` is a value of type `Range` which implements the `Iterator` trait.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The code within the curly braces is applied to each element returned by the iterator.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Iterators can be combined with functions over iterators like `map`, `filter`, and `sum`.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] More generally, the `loop` keyword allows repeating a portion of code until a `break` occurs.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] `break` may optionally exit the loop with a value.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] In the case of nested loops, labels denoted by `'label_name` can be used to break an outer loop rather than the innermost loop.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The `match` and `if let` expressions can be used for pattern matching.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust is strongly typed and statically typed, meaning that the types of all variables must be known at compilation time.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Assigning a value of a particular type to a differently typed variable causes a compilation error.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Type inference is used to determine the type of variables if unspecified.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The type `()`, called the "unit type" in Rust, is a concrete type that has exactly one value.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] It occupies no memory (as it represents the absence of value).
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] All functions that do not have an indicated return type implicitly return `()`.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] It is similar to `void` in other C-style languages; however, `void` denotes the absence of a type and cannot have any value.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The default integer type is `i32`, and the default floating point type is `f64`.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] If the type of a literal number is not explicitly provided, it is either inferred from the context or the default type is used.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Integer types in Rust are named based on the signedness and the number of bits the type takes.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, `i32` is a signed integer that takes 32 bits of storage, whereas `u8` is unsigned and only takes 8 bits of storage.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] `isize` and `usize` take storage depending on the memory address bus width of the compilation target.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, when building for 32-bit targets, both types will take up 32 bits of space.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals are in base-10, but different radices are supported with prefixes, for example, `0b11` for binary numbers, `0o567` for octals, and `0xDB` for hexadecimals.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals default to `i32` as its type.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Suffixes such as `4u32` can be used to explicitly set the type of a literal.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Byte literals such as `b'X'` are available to represent the ASCII value (as a `u8`) of a specific character.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The Boolean type is referred to as `bool` which can take a value of either `true` or `false`.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] A `char` takes up 32 bits of space and represents a Unicode scalar value: a Unicode codepoint that is not a surrogate.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] IEEE 754 floating point numbers are supported with `f32` for single precision floats and `f64` for double precision floats.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Compound types can contain multiple values.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Tuples are fixed-size lists that can contain values whose types can be different.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Arrays are fixed-size lists whose values are of the same type.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's ownership system consists of rules that ensure memory safety without using a garbage collector.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] At compile time, each value must be attached to a variable called the *owner* of that value, and every value must have exactly one owner.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Values are moved between different owners through assignment or passing a value as a function parameter.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Values can also be *borrowed,* meaning they are temporarily passed to a different function before being returned to the owner.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Because of these ownership rules, Rust types are known as *affine types*, meaning each value may be used at most once.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] This enforces a form of software fault isolation as the owner of a value is solely responsible for its correctness and deallocation.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] When a value goes out of scope, it is *dropped* by running its destructor.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The destructor may be programmatically defined through implementing the `Drop` trait.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] This helps manage resources such as file handles, network sockets, and locks, since when objects are dropped, the resources associated with them are closed or released automatically.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Object lifetime refers to the period of time during which a reference is valid; that is, the time between the object creation and destruction.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] These *lifetimes* are implicitly associated with all Rust reference types.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] While often inferred, they can also be indicated explicitly with named lifetime parameters (often denoted `'a`, `'b`, and so on).
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] A value's lifetime in Rust is inferred from the set of locations in the source code (i.e., function, line, and column numbers) for which a variable is valid.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, a reference to a local variable has a lifetime from the expression it is declared in up until the last use of it.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The borrow checker in the Rust compiler then enforces that references are only used in the locations of the source code where the associated lifetime is valid.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] In the example above, storing a reference to variable `x` in `r` is valid, as variable `x` has a longer lifetime (`'a`) than variable `r` (`'b`).
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Since the lifetime of the referenced variable (`'b`) is shorter than the lifetime of the variable holding the reference (`'a`), the borrow checker errors, preventing `x` from being used from outside its scope.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Lifetimes can be indicated using explicit *lifetime parameters* on function arguments.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] In the compiler, ownership and lifetimes work together to prevent memory safety issues such as dangling pointers.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] User-defined types are created with the `struct` or `enum` keywords.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The `struct` keyword is used to denote a record type that groups multiple related values.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] `enum`s can take on different variants at runtime, with their capabilities similar to algebraic data types found in functional programming languages.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Both records and enum variants can contain fields with different types.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Alternative names, or aliases, for the same type can be defined with the `type` keyword.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The `impl` keyword can define methods for a user-defined type.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Data and functions are defined separately.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Implementations fulfill a role similar to that of classes within other languages.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust standard library defines and implements many widely used custom data types, including core data structures such as `Vec`, `Option`, and `HashMap`, as well as smart pointer types.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides a way to exclude most of the standard library using the attribute `#![no_std]`, for applications such as embedded devices.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Internally, the standard library is divided into three parts, `core`, `alloc`, and `std`, where `std` and `alloc` are excluded by `#![no_std]`.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Similarly, Rust's result type `Result<T, E>` holds either a successfully computed value (the `Ok` variant) or an error (the `Err` variant).
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Like `Option`, the use of `Result` means that the inner value cannot be used directly; programmers must use a `match` expression, syntactic sugar such as `?` (the "try" operator), or an explicit `unwrap` assertion to access it.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Both `Option` and `Result` are used throughout the standard library and are a fundamental part of Rust's explicit approach to handling errors and missing data.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The `&` and `&mut` reference types are guaranteed to not be null and point to valid memory.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The raw pointer types `*const` and `*mut` opt out of the safety guarantees, thus they may be null or invalid; however, it is impossible to dereference them unless the code is explicitly declared unsafe through the use of an `unsafe` block.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Unlike dereferencing, the creation of raw pointers is allowed inside safe Rust code.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides no implicit type conversion (coercion) between most primitive types.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] But, explicit type conversion (casting) can be performed using the `as` keyword.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports polymorphism through traits, generic functions, and trait objects.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The example above includes a method `is_zero` which provides a default implementation that may be overridden when implementing the trait.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] In the examples above, `Num: Zero` as well as `where Self: PartialEq` are trait bounds that constrain the type to only allow types that implement `Zero` or `PartialEq`.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Within a trait or impl, `Self` refers to the type that the code is implementing.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Generics can be used in functions to allow implementing a behavior for different types without repeating the same code (see bounded parametric polymorphism).
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Generic functions can be written in relation to other generics, without knowing the actual type.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, traits use static dispatch: the compiler monomorphizes the function for each concrete type instance, yielding performance equivalent to type-specific code at the cost of longer compile times and larger binaries.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] When the exact type is not known at compile time, Rust provides trait objects `&dyn Trait` and `Box<dyn Trait>`.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Trait object calls use dynamic dispatch via a lookup table; a trait object is a "fat pointer" carrying both a data pointer and a method table pointer.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] This indirection adds a small runtime cost, but it keeps a single copy of the code and reduces binary size.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Only "object-safe" traits are eligible to be used as trait objects.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] This approach is similar to duck typing, where all data types that implement a given trait can be treated as functionally interchangeable.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] If an element in the list does not implement the `Display` trait, it will cause a compile-time error.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory and other resources are instead managed through the "resource acquisition is initialization" convention, with optional reference counting.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides deterministic management of resources, with very low overhead.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Values are allocated on the stack by default, and all dynamic allocations must be explicit.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The built-in reference types using the `&` symbol do not involve run-time reference counting.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The safety and validity of the underlying pointers are verified at compile time, preventing dangling pointers and other forms of undefined behavior.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's type system separates shared, immutable references of the form `&T` from unique, mutable references of the form `&mut T`.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] A mutable reference can be coerced to an immutable reference, but not vice versa.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's memory safety checks (See #Safety) may be circumvented through the use of `unsafe` blocks.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] This allows programmers to dereference arbitrary raw pointers, call external code, or perform other low-level functionality not allowed by safe Rust.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Some low-level functionality enabled in this way includes volatile memory access, architecture-specific intrinsics, type punning, and inline assembly.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Unsafe code is needed, for example, in the implementation of data structures.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] A frequently cited example is that it is difficult or impossible to implement doubly linked lists in safe Rust.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Programmers using unsafe Rust are considered responsible for upholding Rust's memory and type safety requirements, for example, that no two mutable references exist pointing to the same location.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] If programmers write code that violates these requirements, this results in undefined behavior.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust documentation includes a list of behaviors considered undefined, including accessing dangling or misaligned pointers, or breaking the aliasing rules for references.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Macros allow the generation and transformation of Rust code to reduce repetition.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Macros come in two forms, with *declarative macros* defined through `macro_rules!`, and *procedural macros*, which are defined in separate crates.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] A declarative macro (also called a "macro by example") is a macro, defined using the `macro_rules!` keyword, that uses pattern matching to determine its expansion.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] In this example, the macro named `sum` is defined using the form `macro_rules! sum {` `(...) => { ... } }`.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The first part inside the parentheses of the definition, the macro pattern `( $initial:expr $(, $expr:expr )* $(,)? )` specifies the structure of input it can take.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Here, `$initial:expr` represents the first expression, while `$(, $expr:expr )*` means there can be zero or more additional comma-separated expressions after it.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The trailing `$(,)?` allows the caller to optionally include a final comma without causing an error.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The second part, after the arrow `=>`, describes what code will be generated when the macro is invoked.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] In this case, `$initial $(+ $expr)*` means that the generated code will start with the first expression, followed by a `+` and each of the additional expressions in sequence.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The `*` again means "repeat this pattern zero or more times".
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] This means, when the macro is later called in line 8, as `sum!(1, 2, 3)`, the macro will resolve to `1 + 2 + 3` representing the addition of all of the passed expressions.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Procedural macros are Rust functions that run and modify the compiler's input token stream, before any other components are compiled.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] They are generally more flexible than declarative macros, but are more difficult to maintain due to their complexity.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports the creation of foreign function interfaces (FFI) through the `extern` keyword.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] A function that uses the C calling convention can be written using `extern "C" fn`.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The `#[repr(C)]` attribute enables deterministic memory layouts for `struct`s and `enum`s for use across FFI boundaries.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] External libraries such as `bindgen` and `cxx` can generate Rust bindings for C/C++.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Safety properties guaranteed by Rust include memory safety, type safety, and data race freedom.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] As described above, these guarantees can be circumvented by using the `unsafe` keyword.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory safety includes the absence of dereferences to null, dangling, and misaligned pointers, and the absence of buffer overflows and double free errors.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory leaks may occur as a result of creating reference-counted pointers that point at each other (a reference cycle) or can be deliberately created through calling `Box::leak`.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust ecosystem includes its compiler, its standard library, and additional components for software development.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Component installation is typically managed by `rustup`, a Rust toolchain installer developed by the Rust project.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust compiler, `rustc`, compiles Rust code into binaries.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] First, the compiler parses the source code into an AST.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The compiler backend is then invoked as a subcomponent to apply optimizations and translate the resulting IR into object code.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Finally, a linker is used to combine the object(s) into a single executable image.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] rustc uses LLVM as its compiler backend by default, but it also supports using alternative backends such as GCC and Cranelift.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The intention of those alternative backends is to increase platform coverage of Rust or to improve compilation times.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo is Rust's build system and package manager.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] It downloads, compiles, distributes, and uploads packages—called *crates*—that are maintained in an official registry.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] It also acts as a front-end for Clippy and other Rust components.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, Cargo sources its dependencies from the user-contributed registry *crates.io*, but Git repositories, crates in the local filesystem, and other external sources can also be specified as dependencies.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo supports reproducible builds through two metadata files: Cargo.toml and Cargo.lock.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo.toml declares each package used and their version requirements.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo.lock is generated automatically during dependency resolution and records exact versions of all dependencies, including transitive dependencies.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] It formats whitespace and indentation to produce code in accordance with a common style, unless otherwise specified.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] It can be invoked as a standalone program or from a Rust project through Cargo.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Clippy is Rust's built-in linting tool to improve the correctness, performance, and readability of Rust code.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Following Rust 1.0, new features are developed in *nightly* versions, which are released daily.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] During each six-week release cycle, changes to nightly versions are released to beta, while changes from the previous beta version are released to a new stable version.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Every two or three years, a new "edition" is produced.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Editions are released to allow making limited breaking changes, such as promoting `await` to a keyword to support async/await features.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Crates targeting different editions can interoperate with each other, so a crate can upgrade to a new edition even if its callers or its dependencies still target older editions.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Migration to a new edition can be assisted with automated tooling.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Since it performs no garbage collection, Rust is often faster than other memory-safe languages.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Most of Rust's memory safety guarantees impose no runtime overhead, with the notable exception of array indexing which is checked at runtime by default.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The performance impact of array indexing bounds checks varies, but can be significant in some cases.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Many of Rust's features are so-called *zero-cost abstractions*, meaning they are optimized away at compile time and incur no runtime penalty.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The ownership and borrowing system permits zero-copy implementations for some performance-sensitive tasks, such as parsing.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Static dispatch is used by default to eliminate method calls, except for methods called on dynamic trait objects.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The compiler uses inline expansion to eliminate function calls and statically dispatched method invocations.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Unlike C and C++, Rust allows the compiler to reorder struct and enum elements unless a `#[repr(C)]` representation attribute is applied.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] This allows the compiler to produce more efficient code in some cases.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Performance improvements in LLVM carry over to Rust.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] In web services, OpenDNS, a DNS resolution service owned by Cisco, uses Rust internally.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Amazon Web Services uses Rust in "performance-sensitive components" of services.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2019, AWS open-sourced Firecracker, a virtualization solution primarily written in Rust.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft Azure IoT Edge, a platform used to run Azure services on IoT devices, has components implemented in Rust.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft also uses Rust to run containerized modules with WebAssembly and Kubernetes.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Cloudflare, a company providing content delivery network services, used Rust to build a new web proxy named Pingora for increased performance and efficiency.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The npm package manager used Rust for its production authentication service in 2019.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] In operating systems, the Linux kernel began introducing experimental support for Rust code in Version 6.1 in late 2022, as part of the Rust for Linux project.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The first drivers written in Rust were included in version 6.8.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2025, kernel developers at the Linux Kernel Developers Summit determined the project to be a success, and Rust usage for kernel code will no longer be considered experimental.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The Android developers used Rust in 2021 to rewrite existing components.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft has rewritten parts of Windows in Rust.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The r9 project aims to re-implement Plan 9 from Bell Labs in Rust.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust has also been used in the development of new operating systems such as Redox, a "Unix-like" operating system and microkernel, Theseus, an experimental operating system with modular state management, and most of Fuchsia.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust is used for command-line tools and operating system components such as stratisd, a file system manager and COSMIC, a desktop environment by System76.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] In web development, Deno, a secure runtime for JavaScript and TypeScript, is built on top of V8 using Rust and Tokio.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Other notable adoptions in this space include Ruffle, an open-source SWF emulator, and Polkadot, an open source blockchain and cryptocurrency platform.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Components from the Servo browser engine (funded by Mozilla and Samsung) were incorporated in the Gecko browser engine underlying Firefox.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] In January 2023, Google (Alphabet) announced support for using third party Rust libraries in Chromium.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] In other uses, Discord, an instant messaging software company, rewrote parts of its system in Rust for increased performance in 2020.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] In the same year, Dropbox announced that its file synchronization had been rewritten in Rust.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Facebook (Meta) used Rust to redesign its system that manages source code for internal projects.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] In the 2025 Stack Overflow Developer Survey, 14.8% of respondents had recently done extensive development in Rust.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The survey named Rust the "most admired programming language" annually from 2016 to 2025 (inclusive), as measured by the number of existing developers interested in continuing to work in the language.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2025, 29.2% of developers not currently working in Rust expressed an interest in doing so.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's safety and performance have been investigated in programming languages research.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] In other fields, a journal article published to *Proceedings of the International Astronomical Union* used Rust to simulate multi-planet systems.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] An article published in *Nature* shared stories of bioinformaticians using Rust.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Both articles cited Rust's performance and safety as advantages, and the learning curve as being a primary drawback to Rust adoption.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The 2025 DARPA project TRACTOR aims to automatically translate C to Rust using techniques such as static analysis, dynamic analysis, and large language models.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] According to the *MIT Technology Review*, the Rust community has been seen as "unusually friendly" to newcomers and particularly attracted people from the queer community, partly due to its code of conduct.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] Inclusiveness has been cited as an important factor for some Rust developers.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The official Rust blog collects and publishes demographic data each year.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The **Rust Foundation** is a non-profit membership organization incorporated in United States; it manages the Rust trademark, infrastructure, and assets.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] It was established on February 8, 2021, with five founding corporate members (Amazon Web Services, Huawei, Google, Microsoft, and Mozilla).
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The foundation's board was chaired by Shane Miller, with Ashley Williams as interim executive director.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] In late 2021, Rebecca Rumbul became executive director and CEO.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust project is maintained by 8 top-level *teams* as of November 2025: the leadership council, compiler team, dev tools team, infrastructure team, language team, launching pad, library team, and moderation team.
[src:tonic-grpc-rust/rust-programming-language] The leadership council oversees the project and is formed by representatives among the other teams.
